#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:108
msgid "Shortcuts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:110
msgid ""
"The pattern above is familiar to `!psycopg2` users. However, Psycopg 3 also "
"exposes a few simple extensions which make the above pattern leaner:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:113
msgid ""
"the `Connection` objects exposes an `~Connection.execute()` method, "
"equivalent to creating a cursor, calling its `~Cursor.execute()` method, and "
"returning it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:117
msgid ""
"# In Psycopg 2\n"
"cur = conn.cursor()\n"
"cur.execute(...)\n"
"\n"
"# In Psycopg 3\n"
"cur = conn.execute(...)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:126
msgid ""
"The `Cursor.execute()` method returns `!self`. This means that you can chain "
"a fetch operation, such as `~Cursor.fetchone()`, to the `!execute()` call:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:129
msgid ""
"# In Psycopg 2\n"
"cur.execute(...)\n"
"record = cur.fetchone()\n"
"\n"
"cur.execute(...)\n"
"for record in cur:\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"# In Psycopg 3\n"
"record = cur.execute(...).fetchone()\n"
"\n"
"for record in cur.execute(...):\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:145
msgid ""
"Using them together, in simple cases, you can go from creating a connection "
"to using a result in a single expression:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:148
msgid ""
"print(psycopg.connect(DSN).execute(\"SELECT now()\").fetchone()[0])\n"
"# 2042-07-12 18:15:10.706497+01:00"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:160
msgid "Connection context"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:162
msgid "Psycopg 3 `Connection` can be used as a context manager:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:164
msgid ""
"with psycopg.connect() as conn:\n"
"    ... # use the connection\n"
"\n"
"# the connection is now closed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:171
msgid ""
"When the block is exited, if there is a transaction open, it will be "
"committed. If an exception is raised within the block the transaction is "
"rolled back. In both cases the connection is closed. It is roughly the "
"equivalent of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:176
msgid ""
"conn = psycopg.connect()\n"
"try:\n"
"    ... # use the connection\n"
"except BaseException:\n"
"    conn.rollback()\n"
"else:\n"
"    conn.commit()\n"
"finally:\n"
"    conn.close()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:189
msgid ""
"This behaviour is not what `!psycopg2` does: in `!psycopg2` :ref:`there is "
"no final close() <pg2:with>` and the connection can be used in several `!"
"with` statements to manage different transactions. This behaviour has been "
"considered non-standard and surprising so it has been replaced by the more "
"explicit `~Connection.transaction()` block."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:195
msgid ""
"Note that, while the above pattern is what most people would use, "
"`connect()` doesn't enter a block itself, but returns an \"un-entered\" "
"connection, so that it is still possible to use a connection regardless of "
"the code scope and the developer is free to use (and responsible for "
"calling) `~Connection.commit()`, `~Connection.rollback()`, `~Connection."
"close()` as and where needed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:202
msgid ""
"If a connection is just left to go out of scope, the way it will behave with "
"or without the use of a `!with` block is different:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:205
msgid ""
"if the connection is used without a `!with` block, the server will find a "
"connection closed INTRANS and roll back the current transaction;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:208
msgid ""
"if the connection is used with a `!with` block, there will be an explicit "
"COMMIT and the operations will be finalised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:211
msgid ""
"You should use a `!with` block when your intention is just to execute a set "
"of operations and then committing the result, which is the most usual thing "
"to do with a connection. If your connection life cycle and transaction "
"pattern is different, and want more control on it, the use without `!with` "
"might be more convenient."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:217
msgid "See :ref:`transactions` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:219
msgid ""
"`AsyncConnection` can be also used as context manager, using ``async with``, "
"but be careful about its quirkiness: see :ref:`async-with` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:224
msgid "Adapting psycopg to your program"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:226
msgid ""
"The above :ref:`pattern of use <usage>` only shows the default behaviour of "
"the adapter. Psycopg can be customised in several ways, to allow the "
"smoothest integration between your Python program and your PostgreSQL "
"database:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:230
msgid ""
"If your program is concurrent and based on `asyncio` instead of on threads/"
"processes, you can use :ref:`async connections and cursors <async>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:233
msgid ""
"If you want to customise the objects that the cursor returns, instead of "
"receiving tuples, you can specify your :ref:`row factories <row-factories>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:236
msgid ""
"If you want to customise how Python values and PostgreSQL types are mapped "
"into each other, beside the :ref:`basic type mapping <types-adaptation>`, "
"you can :ref:`configure your types <adaptation>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:244
msgid "Connection logging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:246
msgid ""
"Psycopg uses the stdlib `logging` module to report the operations happening "
"at connection time. If you experience slowness or random failures on "
"connection you can set the ``psycopg`` logger at ``DEBUG`` level to read the "
"operations performed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:251
msgid "A very simple example of logging configuration may be the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:253
msgid ""
"import logging\n"
"import psycopg\n"
"\n"
"logging.basicConfig(level=logging.DEBUG, format=\"%(asctime)s %(levelname)s "
"%(message)s\")\n"
"\n"
"logging.getLogger(\"psycopg\").setLevel(logging.DEBUG)\n"
"\n"
"psycopg.connect(\"host=192.0.2.1,localhost connect_timeout=10\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/usage.rst:264
msgid ""
"In this example Psycopg will first try to connect to a non responsive "
"server, only stopping after hitting the timeout, and will move on to a "
"working server. The resulting log might look like:"
msgstr ""

